review_blob: 22 oz Bottle.  Pours dark brown, much darker than expected.  Aroma of vanilla and oak.  Taste includes both of those, along with coffee and chocolate, and a noticeable but not overwhelming bourbon flavor.  Excellent winter beer.
2006 vintage, came solid black with a thin head.  Aroma was complex, flavor is very malty with an extremely strong bourbon presence.  Thick.  Very good.
beer_name: Three Floyds Dark Lord Russian Imperial Stout (Bourbon Barrel Aged)

review_blob: On tap at the brewery.  It is a good IPA, but as others have mentioned it is a bit too sweet.  The alcohol is surprisingly noticeable for only being 7.5%.

On tap at the brewery.  Golden pour, fairly cloudy, small white head.  Banana and bubblegum are strong in the aroma.  The taste is like it smells, with a strong addition of wheat flavor. A fairly good hefeweizen.
Bottle.  Bitter, with lots of grapefruit/citrus aroma as well as some spices.  Dry finish.  Would definitely pick it up again.
beer_name: Great Lakes Lake Erie Monster Imperial IPA

review_blob: A bigger version of the Burning River.  Bitter, but not too bitter, with a good balance between malts and citric hops.  Very dry and bitter finish.
Very well balanced, very drinkable.  Not the best IPA ive had but definitely a good one.
beer_name: Great Lakes Burning River Pale Ale

review_blob: Served with nitrogen.  Black with a tan head.  Aroma and flavor both have a roast coffee presence, along with dark chocolate.  Dry finish.
On tap at GLBC.  Dark brown color.  Malty aroma.  Flavor is malt, caramel, toasted, and hops in the end.
Tap @ many places.  Amber color, off-white head.  Aroma of sweet caramel and some hops.  Flavor is sweet caramel and mild hops.  Very drinkable.
Bottle.  Pours black, medium tan head.  Smells of roast and coffee.  Tastes like coffee and roasted malts with a fairly strong taste of hops.  Very smooth.
On tap.  Aroma is roast, coffee, and a hint of smoke.  Black, offwhite head.  Flavor of roasted malts, chocolate, coffee, with smoke in the aftertaste.

On tap @ RRBC.  Light amber with a small white head.  Tastes like a belgian strong with extra hops, along with the flavor of the candi sugar they add here.  Somewhat spicy finish, alcohol is not prevalent but is noticeable.
On tap @ RRBC.  Near black with a medium tan head.  Aroma of roasted malts, chocolate and caramel.  Taste is chocolate with a roasted malt presence.  Fairly dry.  Good.
beer_name: Rocky River Polar Eclipse Double Cream Stout

review_blob: On tap @ RRBC.  Bright red appearance.  Aroma is slight fruit and malt.  Taste is mostly malt with some hops detectable.  One of the better Irish Ales Ive had.
On tap at the brewpub.  Thin white head, straw-golden body.  Smells like blueberry muffins.  Taste is very much like the aroma, light grains with sweet blueberry.  Crisp, clean finish.
On tap at Flying Fig in Cleveland.  Light golden color.  Aroma is grapefruit and floral.  Taste is citrus, especially grapefruit, and some malt at the end.  Alcohol well concealed.  Excellent.
Pours dark brown, almost black with a light brown head.  Aroma of hops and malt, flavor is malty, hops, coffee, chocolate and alcohol.  Very good.
Bottle, similar to the Boston Lager, but it seems a little lighter.  Flavor is mostly malt, with a little bitterness that is almost hidden.
11.2 oz bottle.  Aroma is sweet with a hint of hops.  Flavor is a good balance of sweetness and bitterness in a way where neither is dominant and both are very present.  Mouthfeel is fizzy.

Pours dark brown, black in the glass.  Aroma is strongly of coffee.  Flavor of coffee, along with chocolate, vanilla, roasted malts, and some slight alcohol.  Very balanced, and very rich.  Very good.
UPDATED: SEP 20, 2007
Pours the expected dark color.  Aroma is fairly weak, contains notes of coffee.  Flavor seems a bit watery, also has coffee and chocolate.  Good, but generally overrated.
Bottle. Pours reddish brown, small head.  Aroma of raisins and malt.  Flavor of caramel, raisins, brown sugar, and toffee malt.

Bottle.  Pours pale gold with a medium white head, medium lacing.  Aroma of citrus, and somewhat flowery.  Flavor is malt and hop citrus, with a bitter finish. Medium-high carbonation.  A decent pale ale.
On tap, pours orange/yellow with a white head.  Aroma is the expected cascade hop aroma.  Flavor is citrusy, again typical of cascades, and a somewhat bitter finish.  A good overall IPA.

On tap, pours an almost pitch black.  Small beige head.  Aroma of roasted coffee and chocolate.  Flavor of cream, malt, chocolate, and coffee, with a strong milk chocolate and coffee finish.  Not one of the bigger stouts, but definitely worth getting again.

On tap at the brewpub.  Deep red color, medium white head.  Aroma of malt and honey.  Tastes of malt and honey as well, and also of ginger and some other spices.  Fairly full mouthfeel, medium carbonation.  A very good holiday brew.
On tap at the brewpub.  Hazy golden color, white head.  Aroma is fairly unimpressive, malty with citrus.  Taste is better, wheat and citrus.  Slightly bitter finish.  Very drinkable.
beer_name: Great Lakes Holy Moses White Ale

review_blob: 12 oz bottle.  Pours dark brown with a tan head.  Aroma is chocolate and coffee.  Taste is chocolate, coffee, vanilla, and some roasted malt.  Very tasty.

On tap at the brewpub.  Pours a dark amber, medium white head.  Aroma is very malty with caramel.  Full palate, taste starts off sweet with caramel, and finishes with a slight burn, finish is fairly dry.  Good, but not the best of the style.
beer_name: Great Lakes Loch Erie Scotch Ale

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle.  Pours an orangeish color with a small white head.  Lots of citrus in the aroma.  Thick mouthfeel, flavor is bitter, with a hint of citrus.  Alcohol very noticeable.  Very good, but perhaps a bit too much alcohol presence.
750 ml bottle.  Golden color, decent carbonation.  Aroma is fruity.  Flavor has lots of citrus and other fruits, along with alcohol.

22 oz bottle, 2006 release.  Pours reddish-brown with a small beige head that disappears quickly.  Lots of pine in the aroma, along with grapefruit and alcohol.  Full mouthfeel, the alcohol definitely makes itself known.  Hoppy, fruit, grapefruit, and lots of alcohol.  Very good, but loses points due to the alcohol presence.

22 oz bottle.  Pours black with a tan long-lasting head.  Aroma of dark chocolate, fruit, coffee, and slight smoke.  Taste of malt, chocolate, coffee, caramel, cream, and a hint of smoke.  Creamy body with a slight kick.  Aftertaste of coffee and chocolate.  A very nice porter.
Somewhat skunky, water-dominated flavor, heavy carbonation.  Better than a lot of macro pale lagers though.
Pours a nice amber color, very small head.  Tastes of flowery hops and citrus.  Very smooth.
Amber color with a small head.  Aroma is of hops and citrus.  Flavor is caramel malt with a bit of hops.  Very drinkable.

Bottle.  Of all the light beers ive tried, this is probably the best, which isnt to say its great.  Aroma is faintly of malt, taste is of malt with slight hop bitterness.  Does not taste at all like the normal Boston Lager.
Golden color, medium white head.  Weak aroma, flavor is a little hoppy, mostly watery.  Slightly better than normal american macro pale lagers.
Your expected macro american beer.  Very little taste, very watery, seems to sell based on advertising and the fact that there is no flavor strong enough to be offensive to anyone.
Better than bud lite or miller lite is about the best you can say.  Lack of any real flavor other than the metallic flavor it got from the can.
Very similar to Corona Extra, maybe slightly more watery.  Even ice cold out of the bottle this is barely drinkable.  Very skunky.
Never understood the hype surrounding this one.  Aroma is skunky, flavor is skunky, lime helps marginally.  Definitely best ice cold out of the bottle.  Overpriced.
Malt aroma, flavor has hints of hops and roasted malt but very weak flavor overall.  Perhaps better than american macro stuff, but only slightly.  Very watered down.
Intended simply to get you drunk.  Aroma is metallic.  Flavor of corn, metal, and alcohol.  Not something I want to drink again.

Pours light amber with a small head.  Aroma of lightly burnt caramel.  Taste is sweet, malty, a hint of honey, and somewhat watery.  Not a whole lot of depth.  Very drinkable on a warm day but nothing exciting.

750 ml 2005 bottle.  Pours a dark brownish-red.  Aroma of malt and fruit.  Flavor is rich, roasted malt, caramel, and cherry, with a slight alcoholic presence in the finish.  Bitter aftertaste.  Overall a very solid offering from Ommegang.
On tap at the brewpub.  Hazy gold color with a small white head.  Aroma of bananas and spices.  Tastes of citrus and banana.  Overall a good Hefe.

22 oz.  Pours a golden color with a large white head.  Aroma is very much floral hops, tastes of hops and citrus.  Bitter aftertaste, lives up to the deScription of massive hop amounts.  Good if you are a hophead.
